## Description {#details}

This file implements a <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/targettransforminfo">TargetTransformInfo</a> analysis pass specific to the <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/x86">X86</a> target machine.

It uses the target&#39;s detailed information to provide more precise answers to certain <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#aa0d69e81725c10fa5407f0bf34462068">TTI</a> queries, while letting the target independent and default <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#aa0d69e81725c10fa5407f0bf34462068">TTI</a> implementations handle the rest.

<Link id="l00014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="14"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//</Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="15"><Highlight kind="comment">/// About Cost Model numbers used below it&#39;s necessary to say the following:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="16"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the numbers correspond to some &quot;generic&quot; X86 CPU instead of usage of a</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00022" /><CodeLine lineNumber="22"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="23"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Some examples of other technologies/CPUs:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="24"><Highlight kind="comment">///   SSE 3   - Pentium4 / Athlon64</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="25"><Highlight kind="comment">///   SSE 4.1 - Penryn</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><Highlight kind="comment">///   SSE 4.2 - Nehalem / Silvermont</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><Highlight kind="comment">///   AVX     - Sandy Bridge / Jaguar / Bulldozer</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><Highlight kind="comment">///   AVX2    - Haswell / Ryzen</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><Highlight kind="comment">///   AVX-512 - Xeon Phi / Skylake</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><Highlight kind="comment">/// And some examples of instruction target dependent costs (latency)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><Highlight kind="comment">///                   divss     sqrtss          rsqrtss</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><Highlight kind="comment">///   AMD K7          11-16     19              3</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Piledriver      9-24      13-15           5</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Jaguar          14        16              2</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Pentium II,III  18        30              2</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Nehalem         7-14      7-18            3</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><Highlight kind="comment">///   Haswell         10-13     11              5</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Interpreting the 4 TargetCostKind types:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><Highlight kind="comment">/// TCK&#95;RecipThroughput and TCK&#95;Latency should try to match the worst case</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><Highlight kind="comment">/// values reported by the CPU scheduler models (and llvm-mca).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><Highlight kind="comment">/// TCK&#95;CodeSize should match the instruction count (e.g. divss = 1), NOT the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><Highlight kind="comment">/// actual encoding size of the instruction.</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l07037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="7037"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// vaddps (%rsi,%rdx), %ymm0, %ymm1</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l07041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="7041"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Requires just 1 allocation, i.e., freeing allocations for other operations</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l07042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="7042"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// and having less micro operations to execute.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l07043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="7043"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l07044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="7044"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// For some X86 architectures, this is even worse because for instance for</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
